I ignore the threat to the bishop by attacking black's queen.  If black does not move the queen white checks, trading queen for knight, and can move the bishop later.  Black's best move here is Qd8, to protect Pc7 from the classic K/R fork by NxP.

Here it looks like white erred, trapping the bishop.  But 16. Nb6+ Kc7 would be followed by Nd5+, and the white knight mounts the black queen.  Black doesn't make this bad move, answering with Kd8 instead.  White must trade the knight (or bishop) for black's white bishop to keep the point advantage, though Pb2 is at risk and will likely fall.
